  "prompt": "What is the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to law of inertia?",
  "response": "According to Newton's First Law of Motion, often referred to as the law of inertia, an object will remain at rest or move at a constant velocity unless acted upon by a net external force. This means that the body itself does not apply a force on an object merely due to its inertia; rather, the inertia of the object is what resists changes to its state of motion. \n\nIf you're asking about the magnitude of the force that a body exerts on another object in equilibrium or in motion, it would depend on the specific situation (mass, acceleration, etc.). For example:\n\n- If an object is at rest and no net external forces act on it, the net force (and thus the force the object effectively applies on the surface it's resting on) would be zero.\n- If an object is moving with a constant velocity, the forces are balanced, and similarly, the net force is also zero.\n\nTo provide a more specific answer, you would need to consider additional details regarding the forces acting on the body and the other object in question (such as friction, gravity, etc.). If you were asking about contact forces (like the normal force or friction) or how inertia interacts with other forces, please clarify for a more tailored answer!",
